<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-818-462  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 818 462.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Sept 3 1990 v9 n18 p67(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Imager produces full-color prints from a computer. (Ilford PhotoCorp.'s Digital Photo Imager) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hosinski, Joan M.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   ILFORD PHOTO Corp. (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Photoelectric DevicesPhotographyProduct IntroductionPrintersPublishing IndustryImage ProcessingLasers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Imager Produces Full-Color Prints From a ComputerandM;DALLAS -- Ilford Photo Corp. has announced a Digital Photo Imager (DPI) thatprints and processes overhead transparencies, full-color prints and35-millimeter slides from a computer.andM;Digital input goes from a computer to the digital color printer's imagingengine developed by Greyhawk Systems Inc. of Milpitas, Calif., said James R.andO;Wiley, director of marketing and business development of Paramus, N.J.-basedIlford.andP;  The announcement came at the Siggraph conference here last month.andM;A laser writes the signlas onto three liquid crystal light valve cells inless than two minutes, and then the image is projected onto photographicmedia and sent through the processor.andM;The initial output comes out in 3-1/2 minutes to six minutes, with printcopies produced at a rate of 180 prints per hour transparencies at a rate of120 and 35mm slides at a rate of hundreds per hour.andP;  Copies cost about 75cents.andM;The printer records up to 16 million colors at 300 dots per inch in an8-1/2-by-11-inch format and 3,500 lines on the slides.andP;  The DPI does notrequire a darkroom or special plumbing.andM;Initially, software suppor twill be available for Macintoshes andindustry-standard MS-DOS PCs, Wiley said, but a workstaton version is likely.andM;Optional production management software lets users send job specifications,such as quantity, output media and priorty to the host.andP;  Host software offersshipping, database management and reportng information.andM;About 20 percent of Ilford's large analog photographic color copiers go theDefense Department, Wiley said.andP;  Several defense organization are &quot;veryinterested&quot; in the DPI, he said, mentioning the Air Force in particular.andM;DOD is interested in conventional imaging applications and secure, black boxand remote sensing applications, Wiley said.andM;Ilford is securing a beta test site in the Pentagon, Wiley said.andP;  Theorganization &quot;is a good customer, has the right volume and has shown a lot ofinterest,&quot; he said.andM;Ilford plans to sell the DPI directly to the government and place the printeron the General Services Administration schedule.andM;Beta testing begins this fall, with full production starting next summer.andO;The basic single-host system will be about $50,000.andM;Contact James Wiley of Ilford, tel.andP;  800-631-2522.andO;</TEXT></DOC>